│ I have now inspected the source code of `CorrelatedValuePropagation.cpp` and found that it does not directly handle `AllocaInst`. Instead, it uses `LazyValueInfo` to query for value    │
│ properties. The core of the miscompilation lies in how the value of the alloca `%d` is determined after control flow paths are merged.                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The `runImpl` function in `CorrelatedValuePropagation.cpp` iterates through instructions in each basic block and calls a `process<Instruction>` function for each. There is no           │
│ `processAlloca` function. The logic for `load` instructions is also not explicitly handled in the main loop, which suggests that value propagation for loads is handled implicitly by    │
│ `LazyValueInfo`.                                                                                                                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The problem is that after a pass like `JumpThreading` (which is part of `-O1`), the control flow becomes complex. `LazyValueInfo`, when queried by `CorrelatedValuePropagation`, might   │
│ incorrectly conclude that the alloca `%d` holds an `undef` value at the merge point, because one of the paths leading to the merge does not initialize it. A load from an `undef` alloca │
│ is undefined behavior, which allows the optimizer to replace the subsequent code with `unreachable`, leading to the miscompilation.                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ A simple and effective fix is to make the analysis more conservative by clearing any cached information in `LazyValueInfo` before `CorrelatedValuePropagation` runs. This ensures that   │
│ `LazyValueInfo` re-computes value information on the potentially complex CFG without relying on stale or incorrect cached data from before `JumpThreading`.                              │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ I will add `LVI->clear();` at the beginning of the `runImpl` function in `CorrelatedValuePropagation.cpp`. This is a targeted fix that addresses the likely root cause—stale information │
